	give 10 weeks credit for visiting 10 cities
	(must add 10 to everything though; feh)

	or make them hurdles, eh?  so to do 6-7 one has to visit 10 cities
	8-9 requires visiting three separate regions
	10-11 requires payment of 50,000 gold.
	11-12 requires rank of duke or higher


Must
----

1.  Add a new skill to catch beasts in the wilderness.
    It is similar to wild horse catching.

2.  Make sure BUILD RAFT is documented.

3.  Players may choose from 6-12 cities to start in.

4.  There are no safe havens. (?)  Players are invisible?
    Safe havens only work for your first three turns?

5.  Combat changes.
	Change combat ratings such that peasants, workers, other free
	soldiers can't fight.  But make sure they run away in combat, too.

6.  Get rid of o/0 l/1 in ID's.
	Done in engine, what about mapgen?



Optional
--------

1.  Improve trade.  Trade should make more than taxes.

2.  Add rivers.

3.  Include chart showing what every kind of fighter, beast is.

4.  Morrow "wimpy" mode

5.  Require Persuasion to recruit



Hmmm
----

Max NP's / nobles per faction.

Powerful NPCs with special treasures




Starting cities
---------------

Don't release the vague map?

Game years to get to the edge of the map

Don't have free turns.  Maybe debit people .50 for a turn they don't run.


2.  Don't have wandering beasties attack automatically.
    Lone nobles should be able to explore.

3.  Get rid of the potion of slavery.

4.  Combat changes:

	a.  When a unit is captured, all men with it desert, all
	    beasts run away.

	b.  A unit that is not captured retreats.  Retreat is a movement
	    out of the province in a specific direction.  The direction to
	    retreat may be specified with the RETREAT order.  The unit may
	    not be attacked while it is retreating.  (Should the unit be
	    invisible?)  As soon as any member of the stack stops moving,
	    it loses its immunity shield.  Retreating units drop 25% of
	    their stuff.

	c.  Some kind of change to make the losers be able to get their
	    licks in.

	d.  Some kind of change to allow a superdragon.

	e.  Add a battle magic phase at the start of combat.

5.  Have the Cloud city float around.  Create a rare artifact to
    control its wanderings.

6.  Have Faery hills float around, instead of having the faery stones

7.  Add a Steal item skill to stealth?

> 
> I do not understand why you chose the make a the items all numbers I think
> that some trigraph system would really reduce errors in writing turns. 
> 
> FOR example populations types could be changes from numbers to trigraphs.
> 
> 11 WRK
> 12 SLD
> 13 ARC
> 14 KNG
> 15 ELG
> 16 PIK
> 17 BLS
> 19 SAL
> 20 SWR
> 21 XBW
> 22 EAR
> 24 PIR
> etc

Beastmastery
------------

1.  Improve trade.  Trade should net lots of money.  More than taxes.

1.  Map should be smaller.  500-2500 provinces.


1.  NP's are conserved between factions.

	a.  Potion of slavery goes away.
	b.  New players are given 25 NP's.  No further NP's are ever
	    accumulated.
	c.  TERRORIZE, BRIBE, Persuade oathbound noble require payment
	    of NP's by the aggressor in the event of success.
	d.  Upon death or desertion, all NP's are returned to a noble's
	    owner.

1.  Combat changes, first attempt:

	a.  New combat algorithm:

		1.  All missile fighters get the first round of attacks. 
		    Algorith is as it is now:  choose random victim, see
		    if we hit them.

		    Missile fighters do not fire again during battle.

		2.  Repeat until done:
			Choose a man from each side to fight
			Chance that A hits B is: A / (A + B)
			Otherwise B hits A.

	b.  Eliminate breaking and Fight to the death.  All combat
	    proceeds until every figure on one side has been hit.

	c.  Fog should have effect in combat, just like wind & rain.
	    Wind & rain should affect crossbows & nobles too.

3.  Number of peasants recruitable in a province each month == civ level.
    Recruiting may only be done in cities.

4.  A choice of six initial start cities.  There are no safe havens.
    Instead...  (newbie shields?  invisibility?)

7.  Harvest lumber may only be done instead a lumbercamp.
    Lumbercamps require 500 effort, no materials to create.
    Only one lumbercamp is allowed per forest.

    Quarry stone may only be done in a quarry.
    Quarries require 500 effort, no materials to create.
    Only one quarry is allowed per mountain.

    Lumbercamps and quarries suffer quick damage if left unoccupied.


Other changes
-------------

1.  Consider going to an O3-ish map.  Longer travel times between
    provinces.  Smaller overall number of provinces (200-500).
    All resource extraction takes place in sublocations within
    provinces.  Approx 5-10 sublocs per province.  3 days travel
    into/out of a subloc.  Perhaps a sub-map of inter-subloc routes.

2.  The Cloudlands is replaced with a randomly floating Cloud City.
    Find the key stone which governs the floating so you can direct
    the city yourself.

3.  Big underground dungeon.  Entrances here and there.  Really tough
    dragons down there.

4.  Inland river travel




Setup fee?  $5?  $10?

Longer to travel between provinces.

Winner-gets-weaker combat (see ed bailey mail)

Implement rivers, de-emphasise ocean travel

New-style map?

Get rid of license-plate id's!

Progressive NP costs.  Or a fixed number of core nobles?  Nah, just
progressive NP costs.

Get rid of Use beasts in battle.  Maybe whole beastmastery category.

Better Trade system.

Show toughness of beasts, so one doesn't attack them if one won't win?


Whoa.  One thing we don't want to do is to start getting crazy with
the changes.  We want enough key changes so that the entire _feel_
of the game is different.  New ID scheme, the map idea might do that.
But we want to get G2 off the ground as quickly as possible.


Proposed rule changes
---------------------

1.  Limit Common magic to cities, or tie it to civ level [srt]

> Note that if you adopt Greg's day-by-day PCT4G scheme, this problem
> would disappear. That scheme was that you compute PCT4G on a
> day-by-day basis, allowing everyone trying PCT4G to collect a fraction
> of the available gold, just like peasants or wood or stone or other
> such resources.

2.  Eliminate the diminishing returns on STUDY.
    Instead, characters would be limited to initiating at most
    two STUDY orders per game month.  All STUDY would count for
    full credit, i.e. 1 day's credit for 1 day's study.

3.  Allow GET/GIVE to work across zero time routes.
    Characters could GIVE and item to another character who was
    inside a building.

4.  Allow BUY/SELL/STUDY to work from inside of buildings.

5.  Limit ships to being built in cities.

6.  Instead of Safe Havens, have personal newbie shields.  Last for
    n turns, or until the first ATTACK / HOSTILE / DEFEND.  This lets
    newbies go out and walk around.

    Or at least make ordering random within safe havens.

7.  Install default garrisons in all cities.  100 pikemen or something.
    ADMIT ALL.  PC nobles stacking with the garrisons earn some small
    amount of gold in return for work aiding the city's defense.

8.  Allow a choice of several start cities.

9.  Have a really tough dragon underground somewhere, guarding a
    horde of gold.

10. Look at Bron's sqrt() change to combat side selection, as a
    "walk over" effect reducer.

11. Fog should have effect in combat, just like wind & rain.
    Wind & rain should affect crossbows too.

12. Only allow one building of each type in each location.
    Except towers.  There can be up to six towers in a location.

13. Orders should take constant time whenever possible.  Magic spells
    should take constant time, even for failure -- the time spent
    represents an attempt to cast the spell, even if you don't know it.
    (chance to learn?)  Do everything possible to make predicting the
    turn possible in a rigorous sense, so we can implement a turn
    simulator.

16. Require full term of study in city, not just first day.
    Make a scroll for each common subskill; sell them in the
    city markets.  Require a scroll to learn the common subskills.
    Add [days] to study.

17. Garrison each city by default.  Garrisons are ADMIT ALL.  Players
    who stack with garrisons get paid 5 gold/week.

18. Get rid of resurrection, or make it harder.
    Limit to being used in temples.
    Last Rites is a problem too.

19. Make building castles harder.

20. Make faction growth even slower.  Harder to oath?

21. Allow up to 6 NP and 1200 gold to be spent immediately
    learning skills/developing character right away at setup.

    Setup execution:

	> learn <skill>
	> master <skill>

22. Make the experience scale mean something.  Should take many uses.
    Should display with the character.

	10,25,45,70,100

    Increase amount of wood/etc. which can be harvested.
    Increase ability of sailing, etc.

23. Need a plot.  Call it Olympia G2 -- The Darklands.
    Beyond Olympia:  The Darklands of Areth Pirn.
    Come up with some story about how the sun got dark and evil
    things crawled out of the earth.  The game ends when the last
    vile creature has been killed.

    The player or team with the most ??? when this milestone is
    reached is declared the victor.

    Separate world into areas or islands (nasty forest, underground
    dungeon, etc.)  List how tough the monsters are in each area.
    Start players in a relatively friendly setting.

    Have each different kind of monster have a king, holding a control
    artifact which gives him control of each of his units.

	Orcs Savages Barbarians Skeletons ...

    Dragons are independent.

    No shipcraft, gatecraft.

    Have a ship players can summon for an amount of gold.  It takes
    them into the west, to the land of the dead.  There they must
    defeat skeletons and the undead lord.  There is no return for
    mortals from the land of the dead.

    Also have an underground kingdom with a really tough dragon.

24. Eliminate civ level.

25. New areas, revamp old ones.  Let the cloud city float around;
    have an artifact to control where it goes.

26. Players get a fixed 1-6 primary characters.  Primary characters
    may learn things, do things.  They may HIRE secondary characters,
    and TELL them to do things, but don't get POVs for these other
    units.

27. Mute control artifacts into a new skill which binds a secondary
    character's spirit to the artifact.

28. Let castles be built on islands.

29. Uldim/Summerbridge are a month off.  Should be end of 2-end of 6.

30. Make FLY automatic in MOVE, like riding is.


From lachlan@netcom.com  Mon Oct 24 20:53:17 1994
Received: from netcom4.netcom.com (lachlan@netcom4.netcom.com [192.100.81.107]) by blekko.pbm.com with ESMTP
	id UAA03848 for <info@pbm.com>; Mon, 24 Oct 1994 20:53:01 -0400
Received: by netcom4.netcom.com (8.6.9/Netcom)
	id SAA12270; Mon, 24 Oct 1994 18:39:36 -0700
Date: Mon, 24 Oct 1994 18:39:35 -0700 (PDT)
From: Gerald M McCourt <lachlan@netcom.com>
Subject: two cents <g>
To: info@pbm.com
Message-ID: <Pine.3.89.9410241858.A12215-0100000@netcom4>
MIME-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: TEXT/PLAIN; charset=US-ASCII
Status: RO

Rich, 

This is only the second time that I have liked a PBM game enough to
bother writing to the GM/designer with suggestions.

For a _close_ ended game, Olympia is magnificient!  The ability to
quickely create armies and smash other player positions. Excitement
adventure, romance and blood! After only 17 turns, we have had a
major battle on Mt. Olympus!

For an _open_ ended game however, things seem to be moving awesomely
fast. The AOO is dominating Provincia and more than likely each of 
the other landmasses is soon going to have a dominate group. What is 
going to be the fate of someone who starts the game in six months 
from now? I think that things are moving so fast because everything 
is so bloody cheap.

Beastmasters after a minimal IPL are able to wield large forces at
no charge. Silver tongued orators with Persuasion can acquire large
followings of peasants, again at no charge. Even regular trained troops
are dirt cheap. 

If Olympia is meant to be a _closed_ ended game, it would be nice to
post the victory conditions, so that we non-playtestors know what to
aim for. If Olympia is menat to be a _open_ ended game, I have some
suggestions.

 1. Double or even triple the cost of everything. Do not
    change the income, just the cost.

 2. Implement food and require that beasts, peasants,
    soldiers, etc all be fed each turn, just like the
    peasants & soldiers must be paid.

    Other than putting a price on large armies of beasts,
    the food requirement would now enable a force to
    lay siege to a castle and starve out the occupants.

 3. Change the availability of resources in a province
    to be dependant upon the civ level and the season.

    Peasants, for instance, might be more available in
    high civ provinces during winter and summer but 
    less available during the planting/harvest seasons
    of spring and fall and in low civ provinces.

    Food might be more available in summer and fall.

    Horses might be more available in low civ provinces 
    during fall (after the spring foals are grown up).

Thanx for you time,
    Mike McCourt / faction  vm2
    lachlan@netcom.com

BTW: The rulebooks are great.


Combat idea:
	use that alternative we thought of early in combat design
	a vs. b.  either a wins, or b wins.
	missile fighter works traditionally
	each missile fighter gets to shoot during a round
	other fighters are paired up and duke it out...one left standing


Skyships
Deserts are the seas
Arabian Nights
Magic uses up life -- creates desert

more things to mine
	anamentite
	basis of skyships
	liftwood


tired of plain old regular fantasy
fantasy is neat if its different

more advanced fantasy setting -- technology based on magic
vehicles that are magic powered, "soul powered"
necromancers use people's souls as a power source

sand dragons
vast desert "sea" -- but stuff within it

steam powered railroads

mount some kind of reptile like creature, fly, use them as mounts
ships built of liftwood, liftstone

flying fortresses, flying cities made out of the stuff

boarding battles

a lot of detail in the ships.  different sizes, unique things

colonies exist in the game after the players are gone
have players run cities, "run" the city
sim-city like things

powergamers, powermongers want to RUN their cities
build stuff in it, control the market, run everything

outpost settlements slaves mining ores for the cities
farms ranches

technology; cannons, mostly sword based, perhaps very primitive
firearms

BSE: each position can own 6 outposts

colonies produce things
make it so that colony cannot be self sufficient
basically can survive, but to produce things, traders have
to bring it to you

different kinds of ore
pilot gem / crystal for navigation
governor crystal

caravan -- subset of city position
also gives pirates something to hit
build railroads between the cities, run trains
colonies are where research gets done

black market single character position

Midgard: position types are clans (ship, horse based; military
fighting units); and cities; cities do production
charioteers, neat types of siege weapons, 18 troop types

flying cities, moves on as resources are depleted

ground party, groun expedition, "clan"

Underwater game, hi tech, flavor of BSE
underwater colonies
Waterworld

A lot of naval people in PBM
Warships, ships that shoot torpedoes at one another
naval battles, space battles

twin worlds, sister planet, one's water, the other's desert,
gates between them.

valley, magic surrounding it, dense packed forest, very large,
populated with cannibalistic halflings

very salty or acidic ocean in the desert, lot of metal compounds

suck all life into their continent, use it as a power source for
their magic.

flying carpets over the desert too?  they would wear out, of course.

Out Time Days: most detailed cities ever
	text based detailed descriptions

maybe except for Adventurer's Guild


Separate reports for each different kind of position
Individual reports per noble/position/city/etc.

City armies: training, troop marches, drills, etc.
Each up lots of time.

Unit called passengers that you ferry from city to city.


  10.  A small automatic income for each faction.  (an allowance
from the family?)  Avoids having to make pots or write press for
cash needed to support a minimal entourage.

  11.  Have some starting cities on small island continents
where all provinces are safe havens.  No location building
(except perhaps for towers so peaceful types could research
without fear).

  12.  Allow for castles (and income, though small) on islands.
Would not affect balance much, but would be fun.  Perhaps a better
idea is for some one province continent/islands.


Make map long & thin: the inside of a space tube.
Don't make too many gates.  Seal lots of them.



So far, the changes I have for G2 which address the power problem are:

        o  Make defending easier than attacking.
                Example:  Peasants, workers and sailors will not
                participate in attacks, only for defense.

        o  Elimination of winner-gets-stronger in combat.
                Fighters on the opposing side never get added to the
                victor's inventory.  1/3-2/3 of booty is always lost in
                battle.  Lack of NP transfer means you have no chance
                of getting nobles out of an attack.

        o  A slight change to the combat algorithm lets the loser get his
           licks in before he goes down.  This makes combat more expensive
           for the bully, as he can't attack and come away unscathed.

        o  Beastmastery fixed.
                Beasts require workers for maintenance, and aren't
                as plentiful (one has to catch them like horses).

        o  A reduction in castle income.
                Castles still are lucrative, just not as much.

Some others I'm considering:

        o  Making attacks take more time, say 3 days, perhaps even when
           the target is not found.

        o  Improving the flee mechanics, so you actually have a chance to
           get away (although increasing the attack time as above helps a
           bit here).

        o  Bring back "hyperspace" movement, so one can't be attacked after
           the first day of travel out of a province.  This is really just
           making ATTACK and the display routines work like GIVE, STACK, etc.

These are all tuning level fixes.  They will slow the ramp-up of power in the
game, and together with a limit on the number of nobles allowed in a faction,
may be sufficient to make the game stable in the long term.

Some have suggested changes which I mentally classify in the "Club Olympia over
the head" category.  These include "wimpy" and variants, where we draw a sharp
line between combat units and non-combat units, and spotting rules. These are
all swell ideas, but are big changes, and the level of debate they spark
suggests that they really need playtesting to see just how they behave in
practice.  I'm reluctant to embrace these radical changes unless tuning level
fixes can't do the job.

From morrow@gandalf.rutgers.edu  Mon Jan 23 12:23:40 1995
Received: from gandalf.rutgers.edu (gandalf.rutgers.edu [128.6.7.26]) by blekko.pbm.com with SMTP
	id MAA24150 for <skrenta@pbm.com>; Mon, 23 Jan 1995 12:23:37 -0500
Received: by gandalf.rutgers.edu (5.59/SMI4.0/RU1.5/3.08) 
	id AA23475; Mon, 23 Jan 95 12:25:30 EST
Date: Mon, 23 Jan 95 12:25:30 EST
From: morrow@gandalf.rutgers.edu (John Morrow)
Message-Id: <9501231725.AA23475@gandalf.rutgers.edu>
To: skrenta@pbm.com
Subject: g2
Status: RO

Another thing you might want to consider when making the new g2 map is
to make ALL the lair locations "hidden" except, maybe, islands.  As
people are pointing out, lair cleaning is most lucrative and benefits
those who get in the game first.  As you've pointed out, it is just
too easy to do with an army.  By making them hidden:

A) Players cannot use controlled units to find them, even if artifacts
   only let you control one controlled unit.
B) It will take a longer time to find them all, thus slowing down
   things a bit more (and you want to slow down the game progression).
C) It will make EXPLORE a more valuable command that people will be
   more willing to use more often.  
D) It will partially redress the problem that a roving army can easily
   go on a lair cleaning expedition.  Slowing down an army makes this
   more expensive.

Best of all, you should be able to do this with the exiting game.

The next change I'd make is to make it so that books are destroyed
when used to learn a skill.  This will remove the problem of players
finding more and more books with none of them ever going away.  It
will also make people less willing to share them.

Another change you might want to consider is to REALLY limit the
skills that each city teaches and restrict all magic skills EXCEPT the
basic Magic skill (and Weather Magic in the Cloud Cities) to books
that must be found or maybe to books and just one or two cities in the
world.  Other skills should be harder to find.  Each city should only
teach one or two skills, not a half dozen.  This will encourage people
to go out and explore.  Imperial City might be an exception, teaching
Combat, Shipcraft, Forestry, Stealth, Magic, and Gatecraft -- all the
skills you might need to get started (including Stealth so you CAN
sneak out of IC if you want).  The rest might teach only one or two
skills.

What do you think?

John Morrow

From Dave806459@aol.com  Sat Feb 18 12:59:05 1995
