Date: Thu, 16 Mar 1995 13:30:22 -0500
From: Greg Lindahl <gl8f@fermi.clas.virginia.edu>
Message-Id: <199503161830.NAA89879@fermi.clas.Virginia.EDU>
X-Mailer: Mail User's Shell (7.2.3 5/22/91)
To: skrenta@pbm.com
Subject: faery
Status: RO

The ability of powerful players to use Faery as a superhighway to
quickly get anywhere sort of undermines the ability of players to use
distance to get away from the enemy. Remember when I said that a
fantasy game was one in which it took a long time to cross the world,
whereas a space game was one in which you could cross the entire
universe in 3-4 turns? Well, for most players Oly is fantasy, but for
a few, it's a space game. Hades doesn't really have this effect
because of the fees, although I think that beasts don't get charged,
right? so it's still a bit weird.

From aoo-list-request@cedman.remote.Princeton.EDU  Thu Mar 16 09:36:24 1995
Received: (from smtp@localhost) by blekko.pbm.com
	id JAA26734 for <diplo@pbm.com>; Thu, 16 Mar 1995 09:36:24 -0500
Received: from princeton.edu(128.112.128.1) by blekko.pbm.com via smtp (V1.3)
	id sma026732; Thu Mar 16 09:36:19 1995
Received: from cedman.remote.Princeton.EDU by Princeton.EDU (5.65b/2.115/princeton)
	id AA06979; Thu, 16 Mar 95 09:39:09 -0500
Received: by capitalist.princeton.edu (NX5.67e/1.115)
	id AA29337; Thu, 16 Mar 95 09:39:05 -0500
Resent-Date: Thu, 16 Mar 95 09:38:57 -0500
Old-Return-Path: <cedman>
Message-Id: <9503161438.AA29317@capitalist.princeton.edu>
Content-Type: text/plain
Mime-Version: 1.0 (NeXT Mail 3.3 v118.2)
From: Carl Edman <cedman@cedman.remote.Princeton.EDU>
Date: Thu, 16 Mar 95 09:38:57 -0500
To: AOO list <aoo-list@cedman.remote.Princeton.EDU>
Subject: The Aethelarn Convention
Reply-To: cedman@Princeton.EDU
Resent-Message-Id: <"nJjOD3.0.JA7.7s4Ql"@capitalist>
Resent-From: aoo-list@cedman.remote.Princeton.EDU
X-Mailing-List: <aoo-list@capitalist.princeton.edu> archive/latest/2132
X-Loop: aoo-list@capitalist.princeton.edu
Precedence: list
Resent-Sender: aoo-list-request@cedman.remote.Princeton.EDU
Status: RO

I intend to POST something like this in the next OT.

------------------------------------------------------------------
The Aethelarn Convention on Civilized Warfare 0.1
=================================================

Olympia is a warlike world, ridden by strife and ruled by warlords willing  
to use violence to achieve their objectives noble and ignoble.  And as some  
of us have made clear, we would not want it any other way.  That being said,  
it is still true that there are certain means of warfare which seem to  
inflict much greater harm on the victim than aid the victimizer or otherwise  
detract from the general enjoyment of wanton bloodshed.  We have acted on the  
basis of an unspoken Gentlemans Agreement that such means were to be  
avoided.  Regrettably it has been shown that such agreements aren't always  
sufficient.  Hence we propose the following articles.

(A1) Ban on the aggressive use of Laying to Rest.

Aggressive Laying to Rest of killed enemy nobles to deprive their allies of  
the opportunity to resurrect them is clearly a legal tactic.  Equally clearly  
by statements of the Great God Atnerks it was a wholly unintended one which  
basically eliminates the possibility of resurrection in those cases in which  
it would be most useful i.e. all the major Olympian leaders.  Signatories  
agree not to engage in it or to solicit others to engage in it against nobles  
associated with other signatories.

(B1) Becoming a signatory.

Any noble leading a group of other nobles may become a signatory by  
personally POSTing to the Olympian Times.  A list of other nobles also  
covered by the agreement is optional.  A noble may indicate that he has  
signed this convention or is bound to it by a superior nobles signing of it  
by stating "ACOCW" anywhere in their banner.

(B2) Violations.

A signatory may accuse another signatory of violating this convention in a  
POST to the Olympian Times containing as much corroborating detail as  
possible.  After such a POST the convention is suspended between the accuser  
and the accused until they mutually agree to reinstate it.

I attach my signature to this agreement and consider myself bound by it.
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

What do you think ?  Is it a bad idea ?  Would you sign it ?  Violate it ?

	BtA

From cedman@cedman.remote.Princeton.EDU Thu Apr 20 22:26:04 1995
Received: (from smtp@localhost) by blekko.pbm.com
	id WAA14075 for <skrenta@pbm.com>; Thu, 20 Apr 1995 22:26:03 GMT
Received: from princeton.edu(128.112.128.1) by blekko.pbm.com via smtp (V1.3)
	id sma013948; Thu Apr 20 22:26:01 1995
Received: from cedman.remote.Princeton.EDU by Princeton.EDU (5.65b/2.116/princeton)
	id AA22772; Thu, 20 Apr 95 22:32:15 -0400
Received: by capitalist.princeton.edu (NX5.67e/1.115)
	id AA17164; Thu, 20 Apr 95 22:32:11 -0400
Message-Id: <9504210232.AA17164@capitalist.princeton.edu>
Content-Type: text/plain
Mime-Version: 1.0 (NeXT Mail 3.3 v118.2)
Received: by NeXT.Mailer (1.118.2)
From: Carl Edman <cedman@cedman.remote.Princeton.EDU>
Date: Thu, 20 Apr 95 22:32:09 -0400
To: Rich Skrenta <skrenta@pbm.com>
Subject: NOTES ON G2:  Death Done Right
Cc: AOO list <aoo-list@cedman.remote.Princeton.EDU>
Reply-To: cedman@Princeton.EDU
Status: RO

Apropos nothing at all let me once again point out just how broken the  
current handling of death in Olympia is.  It has all kinds of unrealistic,  
counterintuitive and generally un-fun consequences:

Most of all, Lay to Rest has become the most widely used offensive spell in  
the game.  Anybody, anywhere can do it and destroy a body even if they  
weren't involved in the events leading to the death at all, even if the side  
of the dead body won the confrontation.  Even if you recover the body  
instantly and start resurrecting it at the highest possible speed, it is  
completely impossible to beat a determined LTRer to the punch.

One counterintuitive consequence of this is that Resurrection really applies  
only to minor characters.  If a character isn't worth laying to rest, he is  
probably only barely worth resurrecting.  But powerful or famous characters  
which a seasoned role-player would consider the prime candidates for  
resurrection never get a chance against an opponent with an IQ above room  
temperature.

On the other hand losing any number of those common fear/contract nobles  
with only a few skills has almost no cost at all.  Even if you have no access  
to the body, you can have it laid to rest, used the NP to form a new noble,  
have it study combat and be out recruiting or training again within a month.

Even worse is the horrible lack of realism of death itself.  When a noble  
dies on the battle field, he doesn't just lay down in the dirt as one would  
expect.  Instead he wrangles free from all his opponents without a problem,  
sprouts a pair of wings and flies to the nearest graveyard at a velocity  
greater than that of a speeding nazgul.  Then he buries himself but not  
before sending a telegram to his old boss so that he knows where he can find  
him when he needs him.

With all due (and considerable) respect for you, Rich, this system sucks.   
It is broken so badly that as we have found out any attempts to fix it by  
twiddling with the parameters is likely to only make it worse.  What it needs  
is a complete bottom up replacement.  Of course this can't be done in G1,  
but here is what how I think death should work in G2.

When a noble dies, his body is handled the same way his items are currently  
i.e. if he is in a stack, somebody in the stack inherits the body.  If he  
dies in battle, the body ends up either with the winners, his own side if  
there are some escapees, or hidden in the province.  If a single noble dies  
all by himself his body always ends up hidden in the province.  Hidden bodies  
can be found like any other items by using explore.  A year after the death  
the body is destroyed.  If the body is destroyed either by the passage of  
time or e.g. having its brain eaten, it is just gone.  The old owner receives  
back neither a NP, nor does he even get a message.

A priest in a graveyard who holds a body can lay it to rest.  That destroys  
the body, but recovers all invested NPs for the old owner.  A priest in a  
temple who holds a body can resurrect it.  Resurrection restores the body to  
life under its old ownership but it costs the faction of the priest a NP.   
Together these rules should ensure that only the most powerful nobles are  
resurrected.  Resurrection would be rare and impressive.  Most mortals stay  
dead, but if their owners can recover the bodies and have them laid to rest  
within a year they won't suffer permanently, apart from the hassles involved  
in the laying to rest.

As a side note, under this system high power aura blasts are downgraded from  
killer strategy to mere major nuisance as the body of the aura blasted noble  
will typical end up in the ownership of its allies in the old stack.

	Carl Edman

From desj@ccr-p.ida.org Thu Apr 20 23:45:34 1995
Received: (from smtp@localhost) by blekko.pbm.com
	id XAA15259 for <skrenta@pbm.com>; Thu, 20 Apr 1995 23:45:34 GMT
