From: David desJardins <desj@ccr-p.ida.org>
Received: (desj@localhost) by runner.ccr-p.ida.org (8.6.10/8.6.9) id XAA11284; Thu, 20 Apr 1995 23:51:37 -0400
Date: Thu, 20 Apr 1995 23:51:37 -0400
Message-Id: <199504210351.XAA11284@runner.ccr-p.ida.org>
To: skrenta@pbm.com
CC: aoo-list@cedman.remote.Princeton.EDU
Subject: deaths in olympia
Status: RO

I disagree almost 100% with Carl's ideas of how to "solve" the problem,
but I pretty much agree with him that the whole death/prisoner/last
rites system is a lousy one.

One thing I would add is that Survive fatal wound is the oddest of
things: a very expensive skill (1 NP!) which has *negative* value.  I
just attacked a couple of nobles with SFW this past turn.  Because of
their SFW, instead of being dead, they are my prisoners at health 100.
Which is clearly worse for their owner: if I want, I can always execute
them, but I also have other options like Persuade oathbound noble, or
just keeping them prisoner forever.

Anyway this whole skill makes zero sense and I know I'd be mad if I had
foolishly expended any NP on it.

                                        David desJardins

