From: Scott Turner <srt@sun-dimas.aero.org>
Status: RO

>I probably just won't have Faery in G2...

Oh, I don't think most players want that.  Faery is cool, after all.
It's just (as Greg rightly points out) too easy to abuse as a
shortcut.

Cutting down on the number of elfstones would be one solution
(especially if you remove the apparent automatic protection NPC units
get).  And from my limited experience it seems like the Hunt doesn't
attack that often.  Make them more vicious.  Add 2 elves to the Hunt
for every body that enters Faery. Give the Hunt control over all the
beasts in the battle.  After all, an elf versus a beastmaster?  Who is
the dragon going to obey? :-)

Maybe one of the best things to do would be to make travel in Faery
probablistic.  I'd lean towards a mechanism that shuffles the
connections between the Faery hills, and maybe even shuffling the hill
on every continent between different enchanted forests.  Or, in
keeping with traditional stories about Faery, you could have the
actual Faery locations shuffle around.  It was notoriously hard to
find your way around, you know.  Everything was constantly shifting.
Maybe in Faery you can only move with directions, and every move
shifts all the location connections?  That would be
weird/cool/vicious.  Also, Faery was typically easier to get into than
out of; maybe elfstones permit you to *leave* Faery...

And you should probably eliminate garrisoning in Faery (and Hell and
the Cloudlands for that matter).  I mean, who exactly are you making
money off of in those places anyway, right?

>...beastmastery is already dealt with.

Are you going to charge maintenance?  That's the obvious solution, but
I lean towards a different kind of limit.  Maybe there's a limit to
the number of beasts a beastmaster can control?  And some way he can
slowly raise that?

It would be cool, too, if you had beasts track their ages, so after
breeding you end up with a "young wyvern" that becomes a "mature
wyvern" that becomes a "young dragon" that becomes a "mature dragon",
etc.  Although you'd still have to speed up aging for game purposes.

						-- Scott T.

From pbm.com!news1.digex.net!news2.digex.net!howland.reston.ans.net!swrinde!sgigate.sgi.com!genmagic!bug.rahul.net!a2i!rahul.net!a2i!keradwc.a2i!keradwc 18 Jul 1995 07:50:34 GMT
Path: pbm.com!news1.digex.net!news2.digex.net!howland.reston.ans.net!swrinde!sgigate.sgi.com!genmagic!bug.rahul.net!a2i!rahul.net!a2i!keradwc.a2i!keradwc
From: Kevin Davis Connery <keradwc@rahul.net>
Newsgroups: rec.games.pbm
Subject: Olympia-improvements: Faery
Date: 18 Jul 1995 07:50:34 GMT
Organization: Ringworld Engineering
Lines: 40
Message-ID: <3ufp4a$d3t@hustle.rahul.net>
NNTP-Posting-Host: bolero.rahul.net
NNTP-Posting-User: keradwc
Cc: skrenta@pbm.com

Some possible changes (for Olympia II v2) might be:

1. Faery can only be exited where it was entered (i.e., if I entered at
   aa01, and you entered at bb05, when I exit, I will exit at aa01, and
   you will exit at bb05, even if we use the same exit point from the 
   inside. This fits some classic behavior of the faery lands--though
   it doesn't fit them all.

   This solves the armies travelling VIA faery, but not the takeover OF
   faery.

2. Exit from Faery takes time; perhaps a month or so is 'lost' for every
   week spent inside, perhaps with some random component tossed in. In other
   words, whenever a unit tries to *exit* faery, that unit is in 'limbo'
   for a non-deterministic period of time; consuming no food, making no
   income, etc. This fits some other classic behaviors of the faery lands
   (stay overnight, and leave 20 years later...). If kept to a low but not
   trivial value this would reduce the in-out-in-out casual use of faery, 
   and minimizes the use of it as an army transport mechanism.

3. Make the exit points random rather than fixed. Just because the Faery
   know how to get in and out reliably doesn't mean that everyone with
   an elfstone does. In other words, just because exiting from faery in
   this location gets you to aa99 this time, doesn't mean it will always
   do so. (Or, risking a long term problem, make the exit locations
   time dependent: day of week, or season, or month, or such.)


All of these keep the extra 'space' available for exploration and conquest,
but do not permit that extra space to become a vehicle for other game
distortions.

--kdc


-- 
 | Kevin Connery      | Quality must be designed |         Not speaking for: |
 | keradwc@rahul.net  | into software; it cannot |   Integrated Systems, Inc |
 | kconnery@isi.com   | be patched on afterwards |           Santa Clara, CA |


From pbm.com!news.uni-stuttgart.de!news.rhrz.uni-bonn.de!RRZ.Uni-Koeln.DE!nntp.gmd.de!Dortmund.Germany.EU.net!Germany.EU.net!howland.reston.ans.net!news.sprintlink.net!europa.chnt.gtegsc.com!news.umbc.edu!nobody 19 Jul 1995 18:20:38 -0400
Path: pbm.com!news.uni-stuttgart.de!news.rhrz.uni-bonn.de!RRZ.Uni-Koeln.DE!nntp.gmd.de!Dortmund.Germany.EU.net!Germany.EU.net!howland.reston.ans.net!news.sprintlink.net!europa.chnt.gtegsc.com!news.umbc.edu!nobody
From: schott@cs.umbc.edu (Brian Schott)
Newsgroups: rec.games.pbm
Subject: Re: Olympia
Date: 19 Jul 1995 18:20:38 -0400
Organization: University of Maryland, Baltimore County
Lines: 72
Message-ID: <3uk0fmINNqev@retriever.cs.umbc.edu>
References: <3u6671$qa0@gandalf.rutgers.edu> <3ubvkf$537@news1.ucsd.edu> <3uc9o9$hlp@grapevine.lcs.mit.edu> <3uj7sr$eij@raptor.eng.pyramid.com>
NNTP-Posting-Host: retriever.cs.umbc.edu

The question is: what is the *real* strength of beasts?  When running
the combat simulator (version 1.5) 1 dragon is roughly equivalent to
11 soldiers.

Although though the attack ratio is 500/500 vs. 55/55 the odds are
reported as even.  I think this has to do with the fact that the
dragon has only a 1 in 12 chance of gaining the initiative and must do
so 11 times to win (assuming fight to the death).  The soldiers will
get in a fairly large number of attacks before they die.

If anything, the combat system should be modified to IMPROVE the
performance of strong units.  There is not much of an incentive in the
game to produce swordsmen and knights because the combat system favors
numerical advantage over strength.

I agree that there is an economic advantage to beasts.  One possible
solution is to require a noble-point for beastmastery like magic
skills.  That would at least limit the number of beast masters.
Possibly, also require a noble point for breed beasts.

Brian

---

fight -b 'dr1 * s11'
Olympia II Battle Simulator  version 1.5
Parameters: -b dr1 * s11
5000 battles fought in 4 seconds, 1250.00 battles/s

ATTACKER (Fighting to the death) :

    1 dragon (500,500,0) [0.53]

DEFENDER (Fighting to the death) :

    11 soldiers (5,5,0) [3.77]

    Average losses : 7 soldiers

LIKELIHOOD OF WIN 53.28%
v
----

fight -b 'dr1 * ap18'
Olympia II Battle Simulator  version 1.5
Parameters: -b dr1 * ap18
5000 battles fought in 7 seconds, 714.29 battles/s

ATTACKER (Fighting to the death) :

    1 dragon (500,500,0) [0.51]

DEFENDER (Fighting to the death) :

    18 angry peasants (2,2,0) [6.43]

    Average losses : 12 angry peasants

LIKELIHOOD OF WIN 50.96%



In article <3uj7sr$eij@raptor.eng.pyramid.com>,
Keith Hearn <khearn@pyramid.com> wrote:
>
>I'll bet if beasts started costing in proportion to their strength,
>  you'd see these huge beast-stacks start to melt down to a more
>  reasonable size.





From pbm.com!news.uni-stuttgart.de!news.belwue.de!news.dfn.de!Germany.EU.net!howland.reston.ans.net!math.ohio-state.edu!news.cyberstore.ca!van-bc!unixg.ubc.ca!info.ucla.edu!nnrp.info.ucla.edu!usenet 19 Sep 1995 17:00:28 GMT
Path: pbm.com!news.uni-stuttgart.de!news.belwue.de!news.dfn.de!Germany.EU.net!howland.reston.ans.net!math.ohio-state.edu!news.cyberstore.ca!van-bc!unixg.ubc.ca!info.ucla.edu!nnrp.info.ucla.edu!usenet
From: Rob Rodgers <rrodgers@unex.ucla.edu>
Newsgroups: rec.games.pbm
Subject: Re: "Olympia" - any good?
Date: 19 Sep 1995 17:00:28 GMT
Organization: University of California, Los Angeles
Lines: 36
Message-ID: <43msvc$ake@saba.info.ucla.edu>
References: <42g3qo$1sa@news.ccit.arizona.edu> <4398q1$i2t@blekko.pbm.com> <43isbd$gl8@news1.ucsd.edu>
NNTP-Posting-Host: 128.97.218.117
Mime-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=us-ascii
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit
X-Mailer: Mozilla 1.1N (Windows; I; 16bit)

wbruvold@weber.ucsd.edu (William Bruvold) wrote:

>Noble points are not the problem.  I believe that the single biggest
>problem in olympia is the fact that old players who got a jump on
>the "lair cleaning" during the first few turns have a serious
>advantage over either players who did not participate (largely their
>fault) and newbies (faultless).  This is particularly true as it
>allowed the "capture" of NPC's and control devices, along with
>prisoners.  Thus some of the old factions have in excess of 50
>controlled units, something they did not get through accumulating
>NPs.  While I enjoy the game tremendously, IMHO their is a serious
>flaw in how "labor assets" can be accumulated.  
>

The older players indeed have serious advantage, but hey, why do we play 
this games if not to overcome challenges.  Sure, I would have loved to 
test my skills on an even playing field against the group of older 
players, and perhaps someday I will, but at the same time success will be 
sweet indeed if I can overcome the inherent disadvantages that "newbies" 
have in Olympia.  I'm not going to brag about my acomplishments here, but 
let's just say that at some point I expect to be able to present at least 
a major annoyance to anyone I choose to annoy, no matter how established. 
Success in a game like Olympia is based on the skill of the player, not 
when he/she starts.  

Not to say that there aren't problems with Olympia, but noble points, 
IMHO, aren't one of them.  That system works for me.  Much worse is that 
a noble with 10,000 dragons can enter an Inn...  ;-)

Seriously, Rich, if you're reading this, my biggest problem is that 
access to the areas where advanced magic can be learned are so easily 
restricted.  That, I think, is the major advantage the older players 
have, and it isn't fair.  Either it should be harder to restrict access 
to Faery and the Cloudlands, or the magic skills taught there and only 
there should be made available in other locations.


From gl8f@fermi.clas.virginia.edu Fri Sep 22 08:55:28 1995
