From erik@engrg.uwo.ca Tue Sep 26 10:01:11 1995
Received: (from smtp@localhost) by blekko.pbm.com
	id KAA08975; Tue, 26 Sep 1995 10:01:11 -0400
Received: from nova.engrg.uwo.ca(129.100.100.13) by blekko.pbm.com via smtp (V1.3)
	id sma008972; Tue Sep 26 10:01:08 1995
Date: Tue, 26 Sep 1995 09:53:01 -0400 (EDT)
From: Erik Jacobsen <erik@engrg.uwo.ca>
Sender: Erik Jacobsen <erik@engrg.uwo.ca>
Reply-To: Erik Jacobsen <erik@engrg.uwo.ca>
Subject: Resigning from Olympia
To: skrenta@pbm.com
Cc: MAFOCians <olympia@engrg.uwo.ca>
Message-Id: <Pine.3.88.9509260955.A13568-0100000@nova.engrg.uwo.ca>
Mime-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: TEXT/PLAIN; CHARSET=US-ASCII
Status: RO

Hi Rich


	Sorry to say, but I too will be leaving Olympia.  My reasons for 
leaving are several, but they are all based on my perception that the 
game has not developed in an open-ended fashion.  It has become evident 
to me that the 'power-gamers' of the AOO have in all respects, won the 
game.  I feel that in an open ended game this should not be possible.  

	Some of the flaws in the game as I see them are:

1.	There should be several roads to 'power' , such that no one path 
is far superior to any other.  In this case, the role or importance of 
beastmastery is far greater than that of magic or army-building.  I think 
a proportional balance of power between beastmastery, army building, or 
magic wielding would ensure a greater game balance.

2.	The style of game-play espoused by some members of the AOO ( and 
others I'm sure)  essentially revolves around the 'Harvest of Souls', ie 
acquisition of nobles by preying on new players.  Anyone who cares to 
follow this path of play can rapidly (in fact in an exponential manner) 
outgrow all other factions.  This assumes several things, such as a 
sufficiently large alliance, and a lack of organized counter-reprisal, 
and a reasonably intelligent strategy.  Given that the AOO started the 
game as a large metafaction, and that some of their players were 
undoubtedly very clever, the outcome has been predictable.
	The harvest of souls is the core of the problem.  I have nothing 
against the ability of people in this game to form factions as large as 
they want. But the ability to grow at a rate proportional to the rate of 
loss of other factions means the game is not open ended.  A possible fix 
would be add a combat subskill, 'Death before Dishonour', such that a 
captured noble with this subskill would die before allowing himself to be 
bribed or persuaded.  Another fix might be to simply have multiple start 
locations in the world, although that would reduce the interest of 
exploration.  Maybe periodically rotate start locations to new continents.

3.	My third major nit to pick is the limitation of certain skills 
and resources.  We found that despite settling and exploring 3 or 4 
continents, our faction only found a source for learning scrying around 
turn 55,  and never found any dragons at all.  Maybe we missed something 
fundamental ( ie experimenting with breed beasts more) but as it has 
turned out, we cannot even affect what the AOO does.  It has been pointed 
out that many of the rarer magical skills were to be found in various 
tomes, and that information could be acquired through negotiation, but 
given political uncertainties, it is difficult to make serious inquires 
publically.  While rare skills should be rare, they should also remain 
accesible.
	Also the ability of the AOO, through sheer strength of numbers, 
to be able to control Faery and some of Hades, is unbalancing.  This 
however is a spin-off of Whine #2.  I think however that Hades and Faery 
should remain uncontrollable by anyone at any time, and in fact remain 
dangerous.  Traditional legend/folklore has mortals becoming enchanted or 
entranced if they remained in faery especially if they ate and drank 
while in faery lands.  In game terms, any troops would suffer 10% / week 
losses while in faery, and each noble a 10% flat chance per month of 
being entranced and becoming independent.  Similarly, in Hades, troops 
that drink from the river Lethe would fall alseep never to re-awaken, and 
some due to the sheer horror of being in the Land of the Dead, become 
depressed and wander off to die.  In both cases ( Faery and Hades)  
having large stack especially lingering for a time, would be bound to 
attract the attention of the respective Lords and/or Ladies of the 
Domain, and earn their wrath.  Attacks could be made somewhat 
proportional to the size of the stack

	Relative strengths
'Good guys'								
Native defense
1 noble + 10 soldiers						50%
1 noble  20 soldiers, 10 pikemen,10 crossbowmen		75%
5 nobles 40 soldiers 20 swordsmen, 20 archers, 20 beasts	100% 
5 nobles100 soldiers, 150 crossbowmen, 200 beasts		125%

This kind of an increasing response to increasing forces would keep the 
numbers down, and allow even newbies to explore and travel, while being 
able to survive the trip.  I think allowing Faery and Hades to be used as 
risky routes is good,adding uncertainty to the game, but allowing one 
faction to control one or both regions is game-unbalancing.	

	Despite my criticisms of the game Rich, it is and remains a 
unique experience in game playing.  I have enjoyed both this game and the 
test game immensely.  The ability to conduct diplomatic negotiations is 
great.  The interaction with the other players has been terrific - in 
fact what I enjoyed the most.  The style that we wished to play has 
proven to be non-viable in this game.  We had envisioned MAFOC 
establishing a power base, and acquiring mages, beasts and armies and 
then constantly tweaking the collective noses of the game leaders.  What 
has happened has shown that this is not possible.  Even if the AOO didn't 
have teleporting dragon armies, with the sheer number of nobles they 
possess would eventually swamp all others.  I believe some game tweaks 
are neccessary to maintain the game as open-ended.  If you do start a g2, 
I would love to play again, and as Dan has said I would also be willing 
to throw my $.02 any time.  

				Best of luck

						Erik Jacobsen

p.s. 	the article by Rob Butchko in rec.games.pbm was worth a read -some 
good suggestions
p.p.s.	for every major spell effect, a counterspell	(re teleport/ 
block teleport)



From pbm.com!news.uni-stuttgart.de!news.belwue.de!news.dfn.de!Germany.EU.net!howland.reston.ans.net!news.sprintlink.net!in2.uu.net!dziuxsolim.rutgers.edu!gandalf.rutgers.edu!not-for-mail 26 Sep 1995 17:02:55 -0400
Path: pbm.com!news.uni-stuttgart.de!news.belwue.de!news.dfn.de!Germany.EU.net!howland.reston.ans.net!news.sprintlink.net!in2.uu.net!dziuxsolim.rutgers.edu!gandalf.rutgers.edu!not-for-mail
From: morrow@gandalf.rutgers.edu (John Morrow)
Newsgroups: rec.games.pbm
Subject: Re: Olympia - Time for G2?
Date: 26 Sep 1995 17:02:55 -0400
Organization: Rutgers University
Lines: 47
Message-ID: <449ppv$kre@gandalf.rutgers.edu>
References: <44775c$8ev@saba.info.ucla.edu>
NNTP-Posting-Host: gandalf.rutgers.edu

Rob Rodgers <rrodgers@unex.ucla.edu> writes:
>But I'd like to find out.  Given the opportunity to vote, I'd vote for 
>the opportunity to have a new Olympia world to play in where I'd have an 
>equal chance from the beginning.  (I'd also vote for the skill to build 
>roads, but that's another issue.)

The key to a successful G2 is not that it gives everyone a chance to
start at the beginning.  If that is the only reason for it, then G2
will soon suffer the same fate a G1 if people find it hard to start
after a few turns.  Not very "open ended".  Remember -- this is an
evolving situation with new players all the time and the game should
try to support that.  Otherwise, Olympia will be just another
closed-ended game.

The valid reason for a G2 is to fix the problems that have shown up in
G1 which should, ideally, make the game more equitable and challenging
for all.  The reason that G1 cannot be retrofitted any more than it has
been is that players who have staked their positions on the broken bits
will have their positions destroyed by any fixes.  That isn't really
fair to those players.  G2 would provide the oppotunity to make fixes
and adjust the map to hopefully provide a more balanced game.

As for roads -- fast travel is BAD.  If you can quickly get from point
A to point B, so can everyone else, including your enemies.  Part of
the problem with the AOO is that they aren't just a Provinia problem
(which would be reasonable) but a *global* problem thanks to Scry,
Vision, Teleportation, Faery, and Hades.  If the wilderness isn't hard
to get to (for some reason), it doesn't stay a wilderness for long.
Being able to pinpoint and get to someone (with an army, no less) in
the wilderness in a few short months is a real problem.  Roads will
only make that worse.  I'd personally like to see a map of more
smaller continents although that would require a lot of new names. :-)

>What does the rest of the community think?

What I'd like to know is how many G1 players would jump to G2 and
*stop playing* in G1 and how many would play both?  The reason I ask
is that I think that the people who have spent a lot of time on G1
might get a bit annoyed if everyone jumps to G2 and leaves them in a
dead game.  One could argue that that is what you get for trying to
"win" in an "open-ended" game but I'm still curious. :-)

I think that both games *could* be viable side-by-side, each offering
something a bit different.  But I'd like to know what others think.

John Morrow


From morrow@gandalf.rutgers.edu Wed Sep 27 10:44:34 1995
Received: (from smtp@localhost) by blekko.pbm.com
	id KAA21766 for <skrenta@pbm.com>; Wed, 27 Sep 1995 10:44:34 -0400
Received: from gandalf.rutgers.edu(128.6.7.26) by blekko.pbm.com via smtp (V1.3)
	id sma021764; Wed Sep 27 10:44:29 1995
Received: (from morrow@localhost) by gandalf.rutgers.edu (8.6.12+bestmx+oldruq+newsunq+grosshack/8.6.12) id KAA10280 for skrenta@pbm.com; Wed, 27 Sep 1995 10:43:15 -0400
Date: Wed, 27 Sep 1995 10:43:15 -0400
From: John Morrow <morrow@gandalf.rutgers.edu>
Message-Id: <199509271443.KAA10280@gandalf.rutgers.edu>
To: skrenta@pbm.com
Subject: Re: Olympia - Time for G2?
Status: RO

>> As for roads -- fast travel is BAD.  [blah blah blah :-) ]

>Well said.

Thanks.  Just keep all that in mind when you do the final G2 mods :-).

I think the key is to make it tough for people to shuttle large armies
around and making it a bit more iffy to see at a distance (maybe a
more significant chance of failure for Scry and Vision).  Parhaps
Hades or Faery could work if they only allowed a lone noble in without
troops.  I also had an interesting idea for Hades -- make the prereq
for entry a dead noble and the NP doesn't come back... :-)

John Morrow

BTW - I think the G2 map should be more intricate -- more little
islands, rougher coasts in spots, more significant mountain ranges.
You also might want to consider more stuff like Summerbridge and
the Pass -- and perhaps a sea straight that works like that, too
(perhaps a monthly "high tide"/"low tide" cycle). 

From pbm.com!news.uni-stuttgart.de!news.belwue.de!news.dfn.de!Germany.EU.net!howland.reston.ans.net!swrinde!ihnp4.ucsd.edu!news1.ucsd.edu!not-for-mail 26 Sep 1995 20:28:29 GMT
Path: pbm.com!news.uni-stuttgart.de!news.belwue.de!news.dfn.de!Germany.EU.net!howland.reston.ans.net!swrinde!ihnp4.ucsd.edu!news1.ucsd.edu!not-for-mail
From: wbruvold@weber.ucsd.edu (William Bruvold)
Newsgroups: rec.games.pbm
Subject: Re: OLY: breaking Beastmastery (LONG)
Date: 26 Sep 1995 20:28:29 GMT
Organization: University of California, San Diego
Lines: 94
Message-ID: <449npd$brv@news1.ucsd.edu>
References: <43kn31$9d2@kaiwan009.kaiwan.com> <43ku1i$ti@wahoo.ccr-p.ida.org> <43v38u$45k@stromboli.usc.edu> <445e72$db4@st-james.comp.vuw.ac.nz>
NNTP-Posting-Host: weber.ucsd.edu

In article <445e72$db4@st-james.comp.vuw.ac.nz>,  <bill@rses.vuw.ac.nz> wrote:
>In article <43v38u$45k@stromboli.usc.edu>, whalen@stromboli.usc.edu (Tim Whalen) writes:
>
>|> on ways to balance Beastmastery.  Clearly there is a problem and dragons
>|> are simply the poster children, not the cause of the problem.  The first
>|> time I saw a dragon I told Rich that there was a typo regarding its weight
>|> but I understand that he felt that it was too late to make major changes
>|> to beast stats and breeding odds in g1.  I agree but of course it should
>|> be addressed in g2.
>|> 
>|> TWTW
>|> 
>
>	I agree that dragons should weigh more, but then again I think they
>	should fly too :-)
>
>	My preferred way of toning down beastmastery would be for certain
>	powerful beasts to only be able to breed in particular months.  I
>	can't remember who came up with this idea originally, but I think
>	it has a certain neatness to it.  It also means that for a beastmaster
>	to be able to breeds throughout a year they are going to have to have
>	a better variety of creatures (which is in itself harder to accomplish,
>	and should slow things down).  Finding out the month(s) that particular
>	beasts can breed (and crossbreed) would add another challenge to
>	the game.  Adding a maintenance cost seems a kind of clunky way of doing
>	it and means that the 'travelling beastmaster' type character is not
>	really an option.
>
>B. (who also thinks roads should be added)


Let me add my 2cents about fixing beastmastery.  IMHO, special
months to breed does not solve the game imbalance.
 As a faction with a
fairly large breeding program I would simply adjust to make sure
that my beastmasters had a variety of animals.  Depending upon the
month, I would adjust breeding orders. Dragon breeding now can not
be a monthly occupation but so what?  I still "maximize" my beast
stack and have units that are much more powerful than "human" units.
Again, it takes at least 4 days to create either
 swordman/archer/pikeman
(and more for advanced units such as knight/elite a./elite g.).
These units require maintanence and, because they require
 multiple kinds of inputs (peasants, raw wood/iron, 
processed material, soldiers), it is
often difficult to insure 100% efficiency and coordination

In contrast, to breed beasts takes between 4 and 6 days, requires
little/no coordination, and no maint.  Also no known defesenses
(i.e. wind) to reduce the combat effectiveness of beast armies.
Simply put, except for the ego gratification regarding "men" I see
no reason why mid and old age factions spend _any_ time creating
human armies when they can spend time breeding beasts.  While the
"fodder" argument might hold, I have yet to see a "fodder" dedicated
group of nobles to significantly
ooutpace giant bird/giant spider production over the
long haul.

Hiding the days in which breeding works for particular beasts
hurts newbies and smaller
alliances much more than large ones.  Assuming equal intellengence
leaks", big/old alliances are able to have all their beastmasters
"cover" all beasts each month.  At the end of the cycle they should
know which months allow breeding which beast and which do not.
All this means is that such information becomes valuable and is
unlikely to be shared (it also means that I would kill all
unidentified nobles in beastbreeding area without asking questions
as they can interprete their reports and gain such info).  In
contrast, the smaller alliance has a difficult time "covering" the
possible combinations and so losses breeding opportunites.


IMHO, the best and least intrusive
 "fix" to the beastmastery problem in G2 is to make
beastmastery cost a noble point.  It is a skill that is as valuable
as most of the 1 point magic areas (though I think weather should be
2 but that is a different subject).  It would be difficult except
during the very late game to create 200+ dragon armies _EXCEPT_ if
you specialized in the skill early on.  IMHO, specialization breeds
cooperation/diplomacy which is a very good thing.

In contrast, the fix Rich mentioned early on, requiring support by
way of "workers to handle the beasts" I have decided is a poor fix.
It means that beastmastery _has_ to be associated with castle
ownership (thus reducing the incentives to specialize).  My guess is
that this change will result is fewer "early game" vacuum cleaning
beastmasters (as they will not have the $ to support the peasants)
but that late comers now _have_ to gain castle income to support
beastmastery (thus making it even more difficult to for newbies in a
world in which all land is claimed (and ownership rights enforced by
armies able to move large distances).

Erik


From morrow@gandalf.rutgers.edu Thu Sep 28 01:38:29 1995
Received: (from smtp@localhost) by blekko.pbm.com
	id BAA04030 for <skrenta@pbm.com>; Thu, 28 Sep 1995 01:38:29 -0400
Received: from gandalf.rutgers.edu(128.6.7.26) by blekko.pbm.com via smtp (V1.3)
	id sma004028; Thu Sep 28 01:38:26 1995
Received: (from morrow@localhost) by gandalf.rutgers.edu (8.6.12+bestmx+oldruq+newsunq+grosshack/8.6.12) id BAA04497 for skrenta@pbm.com; Thu, 28 Sep 1995 01:37:03 -0400
Date: Thu, 28 Sep 1995 01:37:03 -0400
From: John Morrow <morrow@gandalf.rutgers.edu>
Message-Id: <199509280537.BAA04497@gandalf.rutgers.edu>
To: skrenta@pbm.com
Subject: Re: Stan
Status: RO

>Sounds cool.  You may want to hold off on chatting with Stan -- I may be
>getting a "web makeover" from another artists, and he said something about
>making my various graphics all have a consistent style.  Not sure what that
>means.  ;-)

You should probably ask Stan, then, for the raw files for the logo he
did so you have it.  Giving graphics a consistent style doesn't mean
you have to toss everything.  My pages look pretty "consistent"
because I cropped and resized all the little graphics icons down to a
regular 72X36 pixel size regardless of the size or shape of the
original source.

>I dumped all of the old design list discussions into hypermail and
>came out with beautiful four-way indexed archives.  And I finally
>figured out that texinfo was a good thing, and turned the rules.texi
>into html with an automated tool.  I'm going to update the manual
>(finally), get rid of all those rules addenda, and put up a proper
>rulebook here.

Hypermail?  What does it index on?  Everything?  Have you seen the
"DejaNews" site (there is a pointer on my search page)?

As for the manual, are you going to maintain seperate rulebooks for G1
and G2 since, I assume, there are going to be some rules differences
or do you hope to handle most differenes via lore sheets?

Another thing to consider which I touch upon in a recent post -- limit
access to lairs to forces of only a certain size so that people will
never get a 100% chance to kill the monster.  If a noble can only
bring 25 other men along, better human units will have more utility
and lairs will have more of the feel that I think you are shooting
for.  The access limit would probably have to be visible.  You could
also turn this back on for buildings.  If people can fit huge armies
into the castle, it will require them to have a second noble hang 
around as a field general.

John Morrow

From pbm.com!news.uni-stuttgart.de!news.belwue.de!news.dfn.de!scsing.switch.ch!swidir.switch.ch!in2p3.fr!univ-lyon1.fr!oleane!plug.news.pipex.net!pipex!tank.news.pipex.net!pipex!howland.reston.ans.net!swrinde!ihnp4.ucsd.edu!news.service.uci.edu!aldebaran.oac.uci.edu!eahg128 Wed, 27 Sep 1995 12:18:54 -0700
Path: pbm.com!news.uni-stuttgart.de!news.belwue.de!news.dfn.de!scsing.switch.ch!swidir.switch.ch!in2p3.fr!univ-lyon1.fr!oleane!plug.news.pipex.net!pipex!tank.news.pipex.net!pipex!howland.reston.ans.net!swrinde!ihnp4.ucsd.edu!news.service.uci.edu!aldebaran.oac.uci.edu!eahg128
From: Mark Hendrickson <eahg128@aldebaran.oac.uci.edu>
Newsgroups: rec.games.pbm
Subject: Re: Olympia - Time for G2?
Date: Wed, 27 Sep 1995 12:18:54 -0700
Organization: University of California, Irvine
Lines: 36
Message-ID: <Pine.SUN.3.91.950927120236.4867A-100000@aldebaran.oac.uci.edu>
References: <44775c$8ev@saba.info.ucla.edu> <199509271434.HAA18374@po.EECS.Berkeley.EDU>
NNTP-Posting-Host: aldebaran.oac.uci.edu
Mime-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: TEXT/PLAIN; charset=US-ASCII
In-Reply-To: <199509271434.HAA18374@po.EECS.Berkeley.EDU>

Erik wrote:

"Which brings up a bigger point, we need more "character" in this
game."

	I certainly agree & view it a shame that the game seems to have a 
kind of cold war mentality (e.g. dogmatix et. al v. AOO).  It is too bad 
that the most poweful AOO factions seem to play the game as a closed 
game.  To put it bluntly, some very powerful AOO factions are not 
civilized.  In a society, groups like this are punished & removed as 
sources of irritation (much like the Brotherhood of the Black Dawn was 
earlier in Olympia).  In Olympia, this kind of play is rewarded (captured 
nobles & control artifacts, captured troops, castles, brain-eating, etc.) to 
such an extent that the AOO just dominates everything.  

	I don't mean to say that this isn't a legitimate playing 
style, it is & maybe I'll play G2 that way, who knows?--but it seems that 
the game rewards it too generously.  It was disheartedning to say the least, 
to find big & very unfriendly AOO armies roaming about the frontier in search 
of newbie fodder.  It adds a little too much cynicism to the game & I 
think recent posts here & in the Times reflect that.  Changes in G2 should 
address this problem.  Here are three suggestions:

1. get rid of the eating of the brains thing.  combined with farcast aura 
blasts & rapid transit through hades to the appropriate graveyard 
presents a significant bonus for the first person to wrench five mithril 
out of the ground.

2. make it harder to convert nobles over from one faction to another (I 
haven't really thought out how to do this).

3. stop putting nobles as treasure in lairs.  This just makes looting the 
ruins way too powerful & is what enables the "vacuum effect" & 
exponential growth (1 lair cleaner turns into 2, turns into 4, turns into 8).

-Mark wearing my game designers hat (first time!)

From pbm.com!news.uni-stuttgart.de!news.belwue.de!news.dfn.de!scsing.switch.ch!swidir.switch.ch!in2p3.fr!univ-lyon1.fr!oleane!tank.news.pipex.net!pipex!news.sprintlink.net!howland.reston.ans.net!vixen.cso.uiuc.edu!news.ecn.bgu.edu!siemens!princeton!cnn.Princeton.EDU!phoenix.princeton.edu!cedman 28 Sep 1995 06:21:53 GMT
