> 6) Teleportation of combat units in coordination with Stealth is too
>    powerful.  It was neat to see once but I'd hate to see it become
>    a normal M.O.  This is something that new players won't have 
>    access to for a very long time.

Never.  Or at least only over BtAs cold dead body.  Nobody outside the AOO
has ever acquired Advanced Sorcery and lived.  Matter of fact, it was only
last month that the second mage rose to the rank of advanced sorcerers
(with BtAs blessing).  I hope that gives something to think about to those
otherwise usually well-informed nobles who, when the first auraculum was
forged almost five olympian years ago, couldn't help themselves but had to
make jokes about "premature auraculation". 

	Carl Edman


From pbm.com!news.uni-stuttgart.de!news.belwue.de!news.dfn.de!Germany.EU.net!howland.reston.ans.net!swrinde!tank.news.pipex.net!pipex!news.sprintlink.net!in1.uu.net!comp.vuw.ac.nz!bill 28 Sep 1995 20:41:12 GMT
Path: pbm.com!news.uni-stuttgart.de!news.belwue.de!news.dfn.de!Germany.EU.net!howland.reston.ans.net!swrinde!tank.news.pipex.net!pipex!news.sprintlink.net!in1.uu.net!comp.vuw.ac.nz!bill
From: bill@rses.vuw.ac.nz (Bill Viggers)
Newsgroups: rec.games.pbm
Subject: Re: Olympia - Time for G2?
Date: 28 Sep 1995 20:41:12 GMT
Organization: Research School of Earth Sciences, Victoria University of Wellington, New Zealand.
Lines: 42
Distribution: world
Message-ID: <44f198$81k@st-james.comp.vuw.ac.nz>
References: <44775c$8ev@saba.info.ucla.edu>    <449ppv$kre@gandalf.rutgers.edu> <DFJE4u.46x@isltd.insignia.com>
NNTP-Posting-Host: dope.geog.vuw.ac.nz

In article <DFJE4u.46x@isltd.insignia.com>, jeremy@insignia.com (Jeremy Maiden) writes:
|> 
|> For a radical option: consider the Supernova II system where new
|> regions start when enough new players are ready, and initially run
|> independently. But, suitable high tech advances allow you to move
|> between regions.

	The problem here is that if you have suitable high tech (read magic)
	then there is nothing to stop you using that to dominate the new world
	you go into as well.

|> Naturally, there have to be limits that stop big g1 armies just
|> conquering g2 (SN has some percentage of things passing through
|> the "gate"s destroyed). Even so, it might be able to provide
|> virgin territory for new players while keeping players in g1 with
|> the thought that their wizards can one day cross over.

	Even if only nobles were able to transit between games, and were
	stripped of all accompanying creatures (and presumably items, as
	well), that doesn't solve the problem.  Assume everyone other than
	AOO abandoned G1 for the new realm G2 (starting anew over there),
	that leaves the AOO (or whoever) free to develop their characters in
	a TOTALLY SAFE ENVIRONMENT.  Presumably at the moment a large proportion
	of AOO effort goes in to wiping out other players and making sure their
	own defences are tight.  Take away that restriction and they really
	can grown without any limits, drip feeding nobles over into the new
	game as they become powerful enough to be lords in the new realm.

	I'd prefer to see radical changes in g1, things like the earthquakes and
	such that were mentioned many months ago in this very forum.  Such a 
	change could be accomplished as the result of some kind of quest proposed
	by the gods, and would thus give the wicked AOO something to concentrate
	on (stopping) other than killing off newbies (who knows, the dark gods 
	that the AOO worships, may have some kind of quest that is set to them), 
	Even the AOO has limited resources.  Twenty or thirty players cannot take 
	on the other one hundred and fifty odd players indefinitly.

	On the subject of changes, I think a new gatemastery spell to locate the
	far side of gates would be a worthwhile addition.  It would be nice to
	have some way of researching new spells and skills.
	
B.

From tpt2@BBN.COM Mon Oct  2 14:39:50 1995
Received: (from smtp@localhost) by blekko.pbm.com
	id OAA03774; Mon, 2 Oct 1995 14:39:50 -0400
From: tpt2@BBN.COM
Message-Id: <199510021839.OAA03774@blekko.pbm.com>
Received: from medea.bbn.com(128.89.5.128) by blekko.pbm.com via smtp (V1.3)
	id sma003772; Mon Oct  2 14:39:42 1995
To: skrenta@pbm.com, info@pbm.com
Subject: Design Request For G2 (Short! :)
Date: Mon, 02 Oct 95 14:32:54 -0400
Status: RO


	I think it would be good if only a priest in a slain noble's
faction had the ability to perform Last Rites on that noble. Better
yet, you could expand the group to include factions that were on the
noble's ADMIT list when he died. 
	The reason for this is that with the current design, we have
people shutting down their enemies' nobles with Last Rites following
up a battle (or an aura blast.) As well as being very silly, it is too
easy for people to siphon off the serious investments of other
players. I'd like to see Olympia move more in the direction where
there's a fair chance of knocking someone down, but it's difficult to
knock someone out.

	Tom	:-)

From pbm.com!news.uni-stuttgart.de!news.belwue.de!news.dfn.de!Germany.EU.net!howland.reston.ans.net!news.sprintlink.net!simtel!zombie.ncsc.mil!cs.umd.edu!haven.umd.edu!news.umbc.edu!nobody 2 Oct 1995 09:20:42 -0400
Path: pbm.com!news.uni-stuttgart.de!news.belwue.de!news.dfn.de!Germany.EU.net!howland.reston.ans.net!news.sprintlink.net!simtel!zombie.ncsc.mil!cs.umd.edu!haven.umd.edu!news.umbc.edu!nobody
From: schott@cs.umbc.edu (Brian Schott)
Newsgroups: rec.games.pbm
Subject: Re: OLY: breaking Beastmastery
Date: 2 Oct 1995 09:20:42 -0400
Organization: University of Maryland, Baltimore County
Lines: 46
Message-ID: <44oovaINN9h1@retriever.cs.umbc.edu>
References: <43mvhl$ne8@mozo.cc.purdue.edu> <43na73$4po@cnn.Princeton.EDU> <43pggmINNoha@retriever.cs.umbc.edu> <DFsEE9.I9D@murdoch.acc.Virginia.EDU>
NNTP-Posting-Host: retriever.cs.umbc.edu
NNTP-Posting-User: schott

I'm glad to hear that more experienced players also have reached the
same conclusion.  I thought I might be missing something.  It appears
that pikemen and crossbowmen/archers *are* sort of optimal given
limited noble time and a game system that favors length over strength
(at least according to the battle simulator which could be incorrect).
This means that a significant number of skills are less than useful
(mining, for example).  It is also a disincentive to trade for scarce
resources (wood and peasants are plentiful; horses and iron less so).

It is interesting that you point out that in Hades where there is a
limit on the number of men stronger units are useful.  Maybe a similar
limitation (number of men in a single stack) would help outside Hades?  

Another idea is to allow Knights to act as independent units sort of
like NPCs with a *very* limited set of orders (move, attack, explore,
seek, etc.)  Combine this with the idea of limiting the number of men
in a stack that can participate in an attack and you add depth to the
game.

Brian Schott

In article <DFsEE9.I9D@murdoch.acc.Virginia.EDU>,
Greg Lindahl <gl8f@fermi.clas.Virginia.EDU> wrote:
>In article <43pggmINNoha@retriever.cs.umbc.edu>,
>Brian Schott <schott@cs.umbc.edu> wrote:
>
>>One of the limitations of the combat system is that there is little
>>incentive (that I can see) for expending the effort of producing
>>stronger non-beast units.  A Knight requires too much effort for the
>>benefit
>
>While I have no use for riding-speed humans, I could imagine that
>others do. If there were an area, like Hades but with no teleport
>loophole, where you were limited in the number of humans you could
>bring in, then there would be more incentive to build stronger humans.
>For right now, I don't build much more than pikemen myself; they're
>great at providing a hard-to-kill target for enemy fodder. One
>memorable combat between Dogmatix and BtA's army resulted in Dogmatix
>losing almost no men because BtA's huge army of savages couldn't get
>through Dogmatix's front line of pikemen. So there are some nice
>trade-offs in the current game, but the expensive humans aren't really
>viable options.
>
>-- greg



From pbm.com!news.uni-stuttgart.de!rz.uni-karlsruhe.de!nntp.gmd.de!newsserver.jvnc.net!newsserver2.jvnc.net!howland.reston.ans.net!news.sprintlink.net!in1.uu.net!hearst.acc.Virginia.EDU!murdoch!fermi.clas.Virginia.EDU!gl8f Sun, 1 Oct 1995 20:32:32 GMT
