From gl8f@fermi.clas.virginia.edu Thu Oct  5 10:36:46 1995
Received: (from smtp@localhost) by blekko.pbm.com
	id KAA05747 for <skrenta@pbm.com>; Thu, 5 Oct 1995 10:36:46 -0400
Received: from uvaarpa.virginia.edu(128.143.2.7) by blekko.pbm.com via smtp (V1.3)
	id sma005744; Thu Oct  5 10:36:45 1995
Received: from fermi.clas.virginia.edu by uvaarpa.virginia.edu id aa05133;
          5 Oct 95 10:33 EDT
Received: (from gl8f@localhost) by fermi.clas.Virginia.EDU (8.6.10/8.6.6) id KAA84280 for skrenta@pbm.com; Thu, 5 Oct 1995 10:33:29 -0400
Date: Thu, 5 Oct 1995 10:33:29 -0400
From: Greg Lindahl <gl8f@fermi.clas.virginia.edu>
Message-Id: <199510051433.KAA84280@fermi.clas.Virginia.EDU>
X-Mailer: Mail User's Shell (7.2.5 10/14/92)
To: Rich Skrenta <skrenta@pbm.com>
Subject: Re: Boring Times drivel
Status: RO

> Tell me what you thought of the mixed sf-fantasy genre game
> again (science fantasy?  space fantasy?)

I claimed that you could do the same thing through a fantasy element
like astral travel or teleportation, which would keep the theme all
fantasy, but have the same result of separated worlds. I think that
separated worlds is a good idea, but they need to be separated enough
that you can't get around the separation. For example, Hades in Oly
can still be scryed/visioned/orbed into, you can teleport huge armies
into it, and many players have enough spare gold to carry huge armies
(of, say, dragons) into it through graveyards. So it isn't a good
separated world. A good separated world in Oly might only allow single
nobles to enter it, with only as much stuff as they can personally
carry, and visions/orbs/teleport/farcast can't cross the barrier. Then
at worst you could have your experienced mage cross over, carrying a
billion gold pieces.

> The alternative, I suppose,
> is to try and keep the engine general enough so that both a
> fantasy version and a space version could be created from it.

Well, we've discussed before the kinds of things that I would want to
do with your Oly engine in order to make it space-game-compatible, and
it wasn't so bad.

-- g

From pbm.com!news.uni-stuttgart.de!news.belwue.de!scsing.switch.ch!swidir.switch.ch!newsfeed.ACO.net!Austria.EU.net!EU.net!newsfeed.internetmci.com!howland.reston.ans.net!usc!news.service.uci.edu!arcturus.oac.uci.edu!eahg128 Thu, 5 Oct 1995 08:38:58 -0700
Path: pbm.com!news.uni-stuttgart.de!news.belwue.de!scsing.switch.ch!swidir.switch.ch!newsfeed.ACO.net!Austria.EU.net!EU.net!newsfeed.internetmci.com!howland.reston.ans.net!usc!news.service.uci.edu!arcturus.oac.uci.edu!eahg128
From: Mark Hendrickson <eahg128@arcturus.oac.uci.edu>
Newsgroups: rec.games.pbm
Subject: oly combat simple fix
Date: Thu, 5 Oct 1995 08:38:58 -0700
Organization: University of California, Irvine
Lines: 30
Message-ID: <Pine.SUN.3.91.951005083152.4904A-100000@arcturus.oac.uci.edu>
References: <44775c$8ev@saba.info.ucla.edu> <199509271434.HAA18374@po.EECS.Berkeley.EDU>
NNTP-Posting-Host: arcturus.oac.uci.edu
Mime-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: TEXT/PLAIN; charset=US-ASCII
In-Reply-To: <199509271434.HAA18374@po.EECS.Berkeley.EDU>

Gentlemen:

	If we're agreed that the combat rules give too much emphasis to 
weenie troops (crossbowmen & pikemen) over cool troops (elite guards & 
elite archers), they why not simply increase the values of these 
higher-end units so that they make sense to build?  One would still have 
to weigh the relative advantages of ease of building (wood is easier to 
get then iron & horses) over long range strength.

perhaps something like:

elite guard:  500/500/0

or even high numbers (friggin warhorse takes soooo long to train).

	Combine this with limitations on beasts as people have been 
discussing, & an elite guard doesn't look too shabby.

	In addition, the skills of swordsmanship & defence (& archery 
too) could confer a significant bonus for use (say, an increase in 
ability of 10 points per use at the apprentice level, up to 20 points per 
use high up).  It's amazing to me that people are using these skills 
anyway (note recent GMs report) with their negligible affect on combat.  

	Along the same lines, magic items should be more powerful (swords 
& things).  As of now they're basically status symbols & little more.  
Let one aura be translated into 50 instead of 5 points.  That would make 
that +1000 armor a little more useful.

-Mark

From pbm.com!news.uni-stuttgart.de!news.belwue.de!news.dfn.de!Germany.EU.net!howland.reston.ans.net!swrinde!tank.news.pipex.net!pipex!news.sprintlink.net!in2.uu.net!hearst.acc.Virginia.EDU!murdoch!fermi.clas.Virginia.EDU!gl8f Fri, 6 Oct 1995 14:26:58 GMT
