jeremy@insignia.com (Jeremy Maiden) wrote:

[snip...ideas for diminuishing beastmastery's current power]

I'd like to add something to all you said.Why not implement,a 1-1
relation between the noble and the units stacked with him? For each
noble in the stack there should be a single (combat) beast under
control,not allowing "1 noble 10 dragons" units ,which,despite being
fun and pitoresque are greatly unrealistic .Please note that it is
still possible to have more than one beast in a unit,by having
additional beastmastering nobles stacked within.Perhaps for lower
combat-valued beasts there could be a skill that enabled a noble to
control two or three beasts,but never unlimited ammounts of them,the
fact that they are tamed does not imply they stop being beasts,and I
find it hard to control more than a dragon at the same time :)

>Suitable choices of all the numbers could give a toned down but
>still valuble beastmastery skill, but have a relativly small impact
>on the existing game.

>Jeremy

-AJRendas


From pbm.com!news1.digex.net!news2.digex.net!howland.reston.ans.net!math.ohio-state.edu!uwm.edu!chi-news.cic.net!simtel!zombie.ncsc.mil!news.duke.edu!godot.cc.duq.edu!newsfeed.pitt.edu!uunet!in2.uu.net!newshub1.wanet.net!ucsnews!newshub.sdsu.edu!ihnp4.ucsd.edu!news1.ucsd.edu!not-for-mail 17 Oct 1995 16:40:18 GMT
Path: pbm.com!news1.digex.net!news2.digex.net!howland.reston.ans.net!math.ohio-state.edu!uwm.edu!chi-news.cic.net!simtel!zombie.ncsc.mil!news.duke.edu!godot.cc.duq.edu!newsfeed.pitt.edu!uunet!in2.uu.net!newshub1.wanet.net!ucsnews!newshub.sdsu.edu!ihnp4.ucsd.edu!news1.ucsd.edu!not-for-mail
From: wbruvold@weber.ucsd.edu (William Bruvold)
Newsgroups: rec.games.pbm
Subject: Olympia and Game Theory (LONG)
Date: 17 Oct 1995 16:40:18 GMT
Organization: University of California, San Diego
Lines: 123
Message-ID: <460m9i$fnu@news2.ucsd.edu>
NNTP-Posting-Host: weber.ucsd.edu

Some of the recent postings on Olympia and the need for various
"fixes" got me thinking about some of the macro issues in the game.

Some background-- Game theory refers to the modeling of games.  It
started as a branch of mathamatics and has been subsequently
developed in numerous academic disciplines.  Some of its most
interesting applications occur in social situations characterized by
strategic interaction, those instances in which the action of one
individual are influence by the actions (and expectations of actions)
of others.  Not the best summary but one that can work to save
bandwidth....;-)

1.  The concept of Game economics. 

IMHO, olympia greatest feature is its movement and inventory
features.  Fairly intuitive, relatively bug free, etc.  Its weakest
feature remains its failure to encourage an "economy".  By economy I
mean something generic, the exchange of goods and services between
players out of mutual self interest.  A good example of a game with
economy is diplomacy, in which gains/victory require that players
cooperate, albeit temporarily, with each other.  A game that
has very little economic interactions would be black jack in which
the players all are individually playing against the house and exert
very litle influence on each other.

2.  Why economies develop

Economies develop for a number of reasons and require a number of
underlying factors to operate.  While there is some debate over
this, most agree that economies develop because the actors benenfit
from exchange.  Furthermore, they most often benefit from exchange
because they are each able to more efficiently produce 1 particular
good and then swamp surpluses with each other.  The famous example
concerns British cloth and Spainish wine.

A key concept is that of value added which I take to mean in game
contexts that the interaction between the players adds more value
than simply a sum of the existing parts.  That is, that two players
can do more seperately than if one player controlled all the
nobles.

In addition to the potential benefits of exchange, for economies to
develop requires punishment of
those individuals who "shirk" and attempt to cheat.  Punishments can
range from the powers of the state to ostracism and detrimental
exclusion from future interactions.

3.  Why Olympia doesn't encourage economic exchange.

Simply put, olympia doesn't encourage economic cooperative because
of the limited advantages to specialization. This strikes across
many categories.  For example, post BTA's production of the
Auraculum there has been very little reason to specialize as a magic
faction.  The mage faction, without Auraculum can provide only
minimal services to other factions while they do not recieve
benefits from cooperating with an obvious target.  Another example
concerns beastmastery, either in the old or the proposed "fix" as
there are little benefit to specializing in beastmastery.  One could
go on and on.  IMHO, the basic olympia "strategy" is to simply
exist, building up in all areas at a relatively equal rate.  The
result is that economic exchange is fairly limited between
homogenous looking factions.

4.  the Present form of cooperation.

Many readers have been shaking their heads and yelling "I have
allies!!  What is he saying???!!!"  I would posit, however, that the
present alliances are largely for two purposes.  One is what could
be call the "social alliance."  It makes playing olympia a lot more
fun, you exchange resources, provide assistance in wars, etc. etc.
However, the actual strategic (as opposed to social) benefits of
that cooperation, I believe, can be questioned. 

Second are the so called "meta-alliances".  These are groupings that
exist for reasons outside of the game universe.  They are based upon
associations brought from other games (alpha, beta, non-olympia) or
have arisen as Role playing devices.  But in terms of pure economic
mechanics, their utility has to be judged by the criteria that the
whole is greater than the sum of their parts.  I think that in most
of these alliances there is little "value added" by the cooperation
occuring.

5.  Fixing olympia.

If a goal, and I think it should be, is reforming olympia to
ecourage higher levels of exchange, I propose the following......

a.  Each faction allowed four "free" skills.  Excluding necromancy,
all factions would be allowed to study the first four base skills
free of charge.  This would count across the entire faction, so that
if each noble studies combat it would count as 1 skill.

b.  The next 4 skills cost 1 noble points

c.  The next 4 skills cost 2 noble points

d.  The next 4 cost 3

etc. etc.

However, there should be (and I would have to think about this
carefully), certain exceptions to skills that can be learned by
scroll.  These would not require knowledge of the base skill.  These
should be "end use" skills for products produced by others.  The
obvious one that comes to mind is use beasts in battle.  Thus you
could have a non-beastmaster faction benefit fromt he products that
the beast mastery faction produces.  Other possible candidates are
"build structure" (with the stones others produce) or "catrips"
(basically a minor form of perform common tasks).

Though radical, the advantage of this proposal is that it would
insure faction specialization.  Factions could, of course, last it
out and eventually learn everything.  But meanwhile lots of value
added as the various specialized factions trade goods/services with
each other.  Furthermore, by insuring that a decent collection of
skills can be learned early on, it insures that players will not
feel trapped by the choices that they made.


Erik




From pbm.com!news.uni-stuttgart.de!news.belwue.de!scsing.switch.ch!swidir.switch.ch!in2p3.fr!univ-lyon1.fr!jussieu.fr!math.ohio-state.edu!howland.reston.ans.net!usc!usc!not-for-mail 18 Oct 1995 11:14:22 -0700
Path: pbm.com!news.uni-stuttgart.de!news.belwue.de!scsing.switch.ch!swidir.switch.ch!in2p3.fr!univ-lyon1.fr!jussieu.fr!math.ohio-state.edu!howland.reston.ans.net!usc!usc!not-for-mail
From: whalen@stromboli.usc.edu (Tim Whalen)
Newsgroups: rec.games.pbm
Subject: Re: Olympia and Game Theory (LONG)
Date: 18 Oct 1995 11:14:22 -0700
Organization: University of Southern California, Los Angeles, CA
Lines: 73
Sender: whalen@stromboli.usc.edu
Message-ID: <463g5u$nj8@stromboli.usc.edu>
References: <460m9i$fnu@news2.ucsd.edu>
NNTP-Posting-Host: stromboli.usc.edu

In article <460m9i$fnu@news2.ucsd.edu> wbruvold@weber.ucsd.edu (William Bruvold) writes:
>
>5.  Fixing olympia.
>
>a.  Each faction allowed four "free" skills.  Excluding necromancy,
>all factions would be allowed to study the first four base skills
>free of charge.  This would count across the entire faction, so that
>if each noble studies combat it would count as 1 skill.
>
>Erik
>

A long while back I proposed an Olympia variant where any single
faction would be restricted to X skill/spell categories.  I'd say
that X should be somewhere between one (a Mining faction would be
pretty dull, eh?) and seven (minimum required for supermagi...)

In alpha I tried to play a religion-based faction and it worked
pretty well but I did dabble in the other categories.  I think
that Rich coincidentally finished the prayer coding at virtually
the same instant I joined the game which made me actually useful
to lots of factions that had written it off as useless.

The specialization in Atlantis II makes it somewhat frustrating.
My job there is sort of like the IRS, basically taxing and giving
the cash to magic research labs and industrial consortia to play
with, as well as some modest defense spending of course.  If one
had to specialize in Olympia IV folks would pine for the good old
days too, I think.  I miss my Atlantis I wizards. :>(

My two cents on the broke stuff is that 99% of it can be fixed by :

A. Adjusting combat ratings (e.g. elite guards), weights (e.g. dragons) etc.
B. Revamping the beast breeding charts to slow down production of good
   beasts (e.g. only chimera + nazgul produce dragons with 25% chance
   for either parent to die and 50% chance of stillborn baby dragon.)
   In other words, dragon breeding becomes almost a zero-sum equation.
   Beasts that fly and/or with high combat ratings should be difficult
   or impossible to breed.  (Sure, why not impossible to breed, for
   instance, giant birds?)
C. Rethinking Faerie, Cloudlands and Hades to discourage the "warp zone"
   concept.  These should be places that anybody *can* get to but that
   nobody can reasonably aspire to "control"  Restrict access absolutely
   to nobles and non-combat items.  (No recruiting, teleporting, breeding,
   capturing, etc.)  Access from Olympia should be dynamic (i.e. locations
   of faerie hills, mountain under Cloudlands, GYs with Hades access
   changes every other game year or something...)
D. Scaling inner location rewards and making inner loc IDs non-sequential.
   Prisoners/control artifacts/magic books should be *extremely* rare and
   require exploration, multiple required artifacts, etc.  Those lone
   centaur guards should have trade goods, artifact weapons or a little
   gold.  Unfortunately, large alliances are able to handle inner locs
   with item requirements better than lone factions but the required
   items are always found within a single region so lone factions can
   toward the netherlands and aspire to success here.

Okay, so it was more than two cents...

-----------------------------------Tim Whalen-----------------------------------

"Whoo-oop!  I'm the old original iron-jawed, brass-mounted, copper-bellied
corpse-maker from the wilds of Arkansaw!  Look at me!  I'm the man they call
Sudden Death and General Desolation!  Sired by a hurricane, dam'd by an
earthquake, half-brother to the cholera, nearly related to the small pox on
my mother's side!  Look at me!  I take nineteen alligators and a bar'l of
whisky for breakfast when I'm in robust health, and a bushel of rattlesnakes
and a dead body when I'm ailing!  I split the everlasting rocks with my glance,
and I squench the thunder when I speak!  Whoo-oop!  Stand back and give me room
according to my strength!  Blood's my natural drink, and the wails of the dying
is music to my ear!  Cast your eye on me, gentlemen!--and lay low and hold your
breath, for I'm 'bout to turn myself loose!" - Mark Twain

-----------------------------whalen@lipari.usc.edu------------------------------

