NNTP-Posting-Host: dope.geog.vuw.ac.nz

In article <463g5u$nj8@stromboli.usc.edu>, whalen@stromboli.usc.edu (Tim Whalen) writes:

	A number of very good points.

|> C. Rethinking Faerie, Cloudlands and Hades to discourage the "warp zone"
|>    concept.  These should be places that anybody *can* get to but that
|>    nobody can reasonably aspire to "control"  Restrict access absolutely
|>    to nobles and non-combat items.  (No recruiting, teleporting, breeding,
|>    capturing, etc.)  Access from Olympia should be dynamic (i.e. locations
|>    of faerie hills, mountain under Cloudlands, GYs with Hades access
|>    changes every other game year or something...)

	At the moment, Faerie and Hades are two of the 'special resources'
	in Olympia that are _worth_ fighting over.  They make trade much
	more profitable.  I like the idea of making access more random,
	I think that would be fun.  But I also think that if you put in
	enough effort you should be able to control them.

	I control the cloudlands and I put about 3 game years worth of effort
	into mapping it out and building a castle up there.  Then another game
	year or two to actually garrison it.  I don't happen to think that was
	too easy.  In fact that was one of the goals I set myself in Olympia.
	
	It would have been even harder if the entrance from the clouds to
	the mundane world had changed every year, but I would still have stuck
	at it.

	Restricting Teleporting into hades and faerie might be an option though.
	If they are somehow separate from the rest of Olympia then it would
	make a certain amount of sense to have teleport not work between the
	real world and those other places.  Or maybe a different spell must be
	researched and studied.

	Recruiting _is_ limited in the clouds (I don't know about hades /
	Faerie).  On a slightly sillier note, so is the summoning of weather,
	Rich, that really should be changed in G2.

	Oh and a final note.  The Cloudlands can't be used as a warp zone.

B. (current ruler of the cloudlands)

